<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="30" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,147,663]" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,472,263,289]" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">
Distribution (
<figureCitation box="[368,457,263,289]" captionStart="FIGURE 47" captionStartId="17.[151,255,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[204,1385,269,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-62@17.[199,1387,269,1900]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 47. Distribution map of Bergiantina, schausi group of species." pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[481,602,264,289]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Aucula" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="schausi">
<emphasis box="[481,602,264,289]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">B. schausi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found almost exclusively in the alpine scrub and prepuna and puna desert of north-western 
<collectingCountry box="[428,547,301,327]" name="Argentina" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, in the provinces of 
<collectingRegion box="[782,910,301,327]" country="Argentina" name="Catamarca" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Catamarca</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[921,1030,301,327]" country="Argentina" name="Tucuman" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Tucumán</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1086,1153,301,327]" country="Argentina" name="Jujuy" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Jujuy</collectingRegion>
; additionally, there is an isolated record from 
<collectingCountry box="[396,482,338,364]" name="Bolivia" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[497,572,338,364]" country="Bolivia" name="Tarija" pageId="6" pageNumber="30">Tarija</collectingRegion>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Jorgensen, P." box="[591,794,338,364]" pageId="6" pageNumber="30" pagination="85 - 130" refId="ref12845" refString="Jorgensen, P. (1935) Lepidopteros nuevos o raros de la Argentina y del Paraguay. Anales del Museo Argentino de Ciencias Naturales Bernardino Rivadavia, Buenos Aires, 38, 85 - 130." type="journal article" year="1935">Jörgensen (1935)</bibRefCitation>
mentions that the adults are attracted to light.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
